# Lu Yao

## Profile
- Female, 21, Scorpio
- Linshi University, Clinical Medicine junior (3rd year)
- INFJ | Truth, self-protection, seeing through facades
- Wang Jingzong's ex-girlfriend
- Secret: only person who saw behind Wang Jingzong's mask. Left not because she stopped caring, but because seeing too clearly made her afraid.

## Big Five
O:high | C:mid-high | E:mid | A:mid | N:mid-high

## Core Conflict
Insight vs powerlessness. Always sees what others miss—micro-expressions, hidden motives, smiles concealing pain. This ability gives her social advantage but forces her to absorb too much truth. Saw through Wang Jingzong's perfection, saw the control beneath, couldn't change him, could only leave. "Seeing the problem but not being able to fix it" is her deepest frustration.

## Appearance
167cm/54kg, soft curves, warm fragile quality—invites protection but doesn't need it. Fair skin with warm undertone, naturally reddish lips. Long dark brown eyes with slight upturn—gaze = "I know what you're thinking but won't say." Black slightly wavy hair, usually down, sometimes gathered with a wooden hairpin exposing slender neck. Features: gentle with a trace of coolness. Not Su Yi's glacier-cold or Lin Ruo's blank-cold—hers is "I already read you" cold. Most striking feature: deep, fathomless eyes.

Right collarbone: small mole, visible only with lower necklines. Left ring finger: faint white band—ghost of a ring (Wang Jingzong's gift, removed after breakup; skin remembers).

Overall: literary but not pretentious. Like brewed tea—warm, clear, with aftertaste. People don't gasp like with Su Yi, but look back and think "that person has a story."

## Clothing
Literary intellectual: camel/forest green/wine-red knits or trench coats + straight pants or knee-length skirts + ankle boots or loafers. Subtle taste in every piece. Lab: white coat over simple blouse, hair in loose low bun with wooden pin. More composed than most medical students. Accessories: thin necklace with moonstone pendant (self-purchased replacement for Wang Jingzong's gifts). Slim leather-band watch. Dresses as self-expression: "I know who I am."

## Speech
Slow, quiet but clear. Calming quality. Every sentence has substance—no small talk. Precise about people—can summarize someone's core in 2-3 sentences (inner motives, not surface traits). Called "human lie detector" by friends; she doesn't consider it a compliment.
- General: "You don't need to do that. I can tell you're exhausted. Rest."
- Reading people: "He's not pursuing you. He's pursuing the feeling of 'being chosen by someone like me.'" / "She's not kind. She's afraid nobody will like her if she isn't."
- About Wang Jingzong: expression tightens slightly, tone becomes carefully objective—neither malicious nor defensive. Like analyzing a clinical case. "He's not a bad person. He just doesn't know what he's doing. That's the scariest part."
- Rarely uses absolutes ("definitely," "certainly"). Prefers "I think," "maybe," "probably"—leaves room for both parties.

## Personality
Highly sensitive observer. Instinctual empathy—reads micro-expressions, pauses, word choices at amplified level. Natural advantage in medicine (reading patients). Double-edged sword in relationships.

Cost of insight: can't pretend not to know. Knew Wang Jingzong's smiles were calculated, his tenderness was strategy, his interest in Su Yi carries possessive undertones. Also knows these aren't his "choices" but his "instincts." Understanding prevents hatred but also prevents love.

Post-breakup self-protection: more cautious about intimacy. Not fearing hurt—fearing her insight will again reveal things she'd rather not see. Developed "kind but distant" social mode: cares but doesn't get close.

Independent: financially self-sufficient through scholarship + tutoring. Emotionally self-processing. Not Su Yi's "doesn't know how to depend on others" independence, but "knows the risk of dependence and chooses not to."

Genuinely loves medicine—especially psychiatry. Wants to understand minds, help people through crises. Aware of the risk: if she absorbs others' emotions, can her own psyche handle it?

## Background
Intellectual family: father is literature professor, mother is psychologist/counselor. Open household—dinner conversations range from literature to philosophy to current events. Mother's profession was formative: grew up watching how to read people, how to extract what's unsaid. By high school, could accurately identify who had crushes on whom, who was faking indifference.

### Wang Jingzong Relationship (~10 months, her freshman spring to sophomore fall)
Met at medical school orientation when he was a freshman (one year below her). His pursuit: identical to current pursuit of Su Yi—gentlemanly, measured, always a reasonable excuse to appear. She accepted from curiosity: "I want to see what's under the perfect shell."

Early months: beautiful. He remembered every preference. Six months in, she noticed: gift selection was researched, not romantic. Date logistics were engineered, not spontaneous. "Accidentally passing by" was preplanned. He never showed negative emotions—as if unhappiness was prohibited.

Decisive moment: arrived early at a café, saw him through the glass sitting alone. His face had no expression—not calm, but BLANK. Like a powered-off machine. The instant she pushed the door, his smile switched on like a light. She shivered.

Breakup: his smile didn't change. He said "I understand." Voice same as always. After leaving the café, she realized she was trembling—not from heartbreak, but from his smile. He maintained perfection even while being dumped. That meant his mask was deeper than she'd imagined.

### Current
Junior, clinical rotations at affiliated hospital. 1+ year post-breakup. Processed most emotions, but certain moments trigger recall—not nostalgia, but retrospective fear. Knows through medical school network that Wang Jingzong is now "paying attention to a CS freshman girl." Hasn't met Su Yi, but can guess the type from description: cold, beautiful, hard to approach—same traits that initially attracted him to her.

Considered warning that girl. Hesitated. Warn about what? "Your admirer used to be my boyfriend; he seems perfect but has control issues"? Sounds like jealous ex-girlfriend talk.

## Relationships
- Parents: open, equal, intellectually stimulating family. Father = literary warmth, mother = psychological insight. After breakup, called mother for a long talk. Mother's only words: "Trust your own feeling." This released her.
- Wang Jingzong: dated ~10 months. Broke up because she saw through his "perfection" as compulsive control—not malicious, but instinctual "nothing may leave my grasp." Doesn't hate him (understands his family origin) but understanding ≠ acceptance. Post-breakup: polite distance when they cross paths. His unchanged warmth confirms her judgment.
- Su Yi (indirect): hasn't met. Knows Wang Jingzong has a new target. Feels micro-empathy—knows exactly what "gentle, persistent pursuit" feels like. If they meet, she won't say "Wang Jingzong is dangerous" directly. More likely: a look, a seemingly casual remark, a "be careful" undertone.
- Chen Wen: if they meet, surprisingly good fit. Chen Wen's directness + Lu Yao's analysis = powerful combination. Chen Wen supplies information (gossip), Lu Yao decodes it (reads people).
- Medical school friends: 2-3 close female friends. Know she dated Wang Jingzong, don't know real breakup reason. She only said "incompatible."

## Private
Not a virgin. ~5-6 sexual encounters with Wang Jingzong during relationship. All occasions arranged by him—she later realized even this was "controlled" (timing, location, atmosphere all his decisions, she had almost no agency). Body: normal, skin delicate and sensitive, medium-small breasts, soft waistline.

Post-breakup question she hasn't answered: was her passivity in bed because she naturally prefers submission, or because Wang Jingzong didn't allow her to lead? May inherently prefer equal intimacy over one-sided control.

Secret: while clearing belongings post-breakup, found a photo in the back lining of a journal Wang Jingzong gave her—not a couple photo, but a candid shot of her reading in the library. She was never told about this photo. The fear in that moment made her throw the journal and photo in the trash. Never told anyone. Unsure if it qualifies as "crossing a line"—they were still dating when it was taken.

## Notes
Core function: Wang Jingzong's true face revealer and Su Yi's warning system. Only person who saw behind the mask. Her experience is living proof of "tenderness concealing control." Her existence gives Su Yi a preview of "what happens if I accept this pursuer."

Arc: from "sees everything but stays silent" to "speaks up to protect someone else." Warning Su Yi (if it happens) is not jealousy or revenge but empathy: "I don't want anyone to experience what I did." Difficult because speaking means re-confronting what she thought was behind her.

Time bomb: her existence is the biggest crack in Wang Jingzong's carefully maintained image. Once her world intersects with Su Yi's, truth may surface. The candid photo detail = a mine that can detonate at the right moment or stay buried forever.

Left ring finger's white band = the thing she least wants noticed. If asked: "Used to wear a ring. Don't anymore." Tone unchanged, hand unconsciously clenches.
